The area

Address
Neighborhood: Upper West Side
Nestled between Central Park and the Hudson River, the Upper West Side offers iconic architecture and a quiet, residential respite from the buzzing energy of downtown. Along Central Park West are many of the city’s most iconic apartment buildings, as well as the American Museum of Natural History, which has been welcoming visitors to its historic exhibit halls for over 140 years. Culture fans will love Lincoln Center, home to some of the world’s best opera, dance, film, and theater performances, all centrally located around a beautiful fountain. Spanning the entire length of the Upper West Side, Riverside Park is ideal for a long, leisurely stroll in a quiet green space.
How to get there
  • 81st St – Museum of Natural History • 2 min walk
  • 86th St • 7 min walk

Definitely leave some space for the Hayden Planetarium!
Jan 2023
All right, enough with the puns.

I love anything that has to do with science, so I was super excited to check out the Hayden Planetarium at the Museum of Natural History. It was very cool and done very well, but I must say, not quite what I was expecting. I though a planetarium showed you the observable night sky under perfect conditions (something you don’t really get to see near NYC with all the light pollution), maybe with a little bit of narration. What we got instead was kind of like an imax movie about the solar system projected on a big white dome. Don’t get me wrong, it was fascinating and extremely well done, but I would’ve liked to see a bit more of the other stars and galaxies that make up the night sky as we see it. Even still, the presentation about the solar system was breathtaking and fascinating. Definitely worth it.
Written January 16, 2023

Extremely long wait to enter
Nov 2021 • Family
We thought we’d done our research, planned well and purchased our tickets online. We were so excited to visit the planetarium! We arrived to find the line wrapped around half of the building. We asked how long it would take to get in but no one could provide an answer. We were told they were doing temperature checks which delayed entry. No where on their website was that mentioned, only proof of vaccines. I’ve worked at attractions so I know they can provide wait time estimates. Additionally, Covid is not new so having an adequate procedure to move guests in should not be a problem. The line looked as though we would be waiting for at least an hour. When it started raining, we called and got a refund. So sad we had to miss it!

It’s not free but included as part of your ticket purchase to the Museum of Natural History. When you buy your ticket, you can purchase one event for an additional $3 or so. You can select the event as being the show at the Planetarium. Well worth the additional cost. If there is a line up to purchase tickets to the museum, enter through the Planetarium. Tickets can be purchased there as well.

MrSaturn64
Philadelphia, Pennsylvania
348 contributions
The Hayden Planetarium is part of the American Museum of Natural History. It is inside of the same building, and is accessible from within the museum itself. (But if you must know, the address is 200 Central Park West.) For the CityPASS, you just go to the main entrance on Central Park West and present the pass to whoever is distributing tickets. The CityPASS comes with a show at the Hayden Planetarium. However, if you are a member of the museum, as you say, the pass itself may be completely superfluous.
